The meeting was called to order by Keir at 4:30 p.m. A quorum was present. Rovney moved the agenda, Wheeler seconded.
Wheeler moved the minutes from August 26, 2014 be approved; Smentek seconded., The motion carried 4-0.
The following agenda items were discussed:
Bode presented to the committee the proposed parking control along the 500 and 600 block of Front Street as
well as the loading and unloading zones along Warren Street and Cherry Street as outline in the memo.
Comments that were received from the city letter that was sent out to the property owners included an email
from Tom Frederick who indicated that they would like like one handicap parking space in front of their
building located at 500 S. Front Street. Other comments from Tom included the requested change from 2 hour
parking 8:00 AM to 5 PM Monday to Friday along his building to include a commercial loading zone from
5:00 AM to 11 AM. Gregg Anderson and Jerry Palmer also indicated the following concerns with parking and
Would like 3 handicap spaces along the 600 block, one in front of 633 S Front Street, one next to the
Walgreens parking lot entrance, and the other in Front of 607 S. Front Street which would include a
ped ramp to the bump out area.
Request for an all way stop at Liberty and Front Street
Concerns with speeds along Front Street as they observe speeds up to 40 mph and that traffic calming
Other concerns included why the City did not consider the installation of Handicap spaces with the
The committee discussed these issues and concerns and recommended the City to go through the normal process
to evaluated the need for the all way stop at Liberty Street and Front Street. This shall come back to this
committee next month with the results of this study. Members noted the comments from Mr. Frederick and to
make the adjustment in the 2 hour parking along Cherry Street to include the additional commercial loading
zone. It was also noted to include the recommendations on the 4 handicap parking spaces noting the additional
request to modify the curb and sidewalk to accommodate a new ped ramp at 607 S. Front Street. This curb and
sidewalk estimate will go before the last council meeting in October for their decision. Smentek moved and
Wheeler seconded a motion to amend the parking resolutions to reflect the changes noted above and the
installation of the handicap parking spaces. The motion carried 4-0.
Bode presented to the committee the reverse angle parking along 511 Holly Lane for Kyle Smith. The parking
configuration would be the first of its kind in Mankato and would be used for employee parking. It was noted
that the sidewalk would be installed along the west side of Holly Lane from Belle Avenue to Madison Avenue.
Unofficial until approved by City Council
The private use agreement is outlined by agreement number 20144. The committee noted no issues. Rovney
moved and Smentek seconded a motion to approve the reverse angle parking. The motion carried 4-0.
6.3 James Avenue and Fairfield Avenue- All Way Stop
Bode presented to the committee the request from school district to install an all-way stop at the intersection of
James Avenue and Fairfield Avenue. Bode explained that this intersection was identified by the SRTS Plan for
the installation of an all way stop as this is the only access to the school by vehicular traffic. Rovney
Wheeler seconded a motion to approve the all way stop. The motion carried 4-0.
10.1 N. Riverfront Drive and T.H. 14 North Ramp.
Smentek indicated that traffics get significantly delayed during peak intervals on the WB TH 14 ramp to access
Riverfront Drive. Smentek noted that cars will make right hand turns and proceed to make a u-turn even though
it is signed as no u-turns. Bode indicated that studies have been done in this area and additional traffic counts
have been conducted and that he would forward onward to the MPO for further discussion.
Multi-Modal Committee Meeting, October 28, 2014, 4:30 p.m., Intergovernmental Center
Rovney moved and Wheeler seconded a motion to adjourn the meeting. The meeting ended at 5:32 p.m.
The next meeting will be at 4:30 pm on October 28, 2014, in the Minnesota Valley Room.

page.text: Following the meeting, the City Manager suggested temporary traffic control at the
intersection for the next 90 days, during which time additional observations will be done
along with gaining feedback from stakeholders in the area, including businesses and
other users (such as the disabled population at Durham who frequent this area). Both
staff and Council members have received feedback regarding the geometrics of the
intersection and the effectiveness of the temporary control can be considered in the
context of the existing information. The issue of a four-way stop at Liberty and South
Front Street was discussed at Site Plan Review but no clear consensus was
formulated. Instead, the committee requested additional information regarding
pedestrian crossings at the intersection. The manager understands pedestrian crossing
were factored into the report from Engineering. However, this information was not
available at the meeting. At Site Plan, I understand there was discussion that the new
roadway configuration did restrict visibility for vehicles on Liberty Street crossing Front
and for pedestrians on the south leg of the intersection where bump outs exist. The
context of the control in respect to the goals of connectivity were also discussed.
However, these are not included within the attached document. These are some of the
primary reasons the manager have heard for support of stop signs. In the interim and
during the pedestrian study, Section 6.02 (below) of the City Code enables the City
Manger to direct traffic restrictions on an experimental basis for a period of 90-days.
During this period, additional pedestrian counts could be conducted and feedback
obtained from concerned parties regarding the effectiveness of the control. In addition
site lines, etc would be reviewed.

page.text: FROM: Landon Bode, Associate Civil Engineer
SUBJECT: Front Street and Liberty Street Intersection Traffic Study
On September 23rd, the Multimodal committee held their monthly meeting to discuss parking
recommendations along Front Street. The 500 and 600 block owners were invited to this
meeting with only Gregg Anderson and Jeffery Palmer in attendance. They indicated that
traffic speeds are in excess of 40 mphs along Front Street and that the recent curb extensions
along Front Street at the intersection of Liberty Street are not effective in slowing the vehicular
traffic. It was recommended by the Multimodal committee to have engineering to conduct a
traffic study at the intersection of Front Street and Liberty Street.
On October 2, 2014, the intersection of Front Street and Liberty was evaluated to determine if
traffic volumes warranted additional traffic control at this intersection such as a all-way stop.
Currently the intersection is controlled as a two-way stop with Liberty Street having the stop
condition. Front Street is a Municipal State Aid Street having the free flowing movement. See
the existing conditions for additional information. A traffic study was conducted on October 1,
2014 thru the use of pneumatic road tubes and video recording where traffic volumes and as
well as turning movements were collected.
An accident study was conducted reviewing the past 5 years of crash history utilizing the
Minnesota Crash Mapping Analysis Tool. In those 5 years, only 3 accidents have occurred at
this location. These accidents occurred at 6/15/2011, 7/8/2013 and on 12/8/2013. These 3
accidents included one with motor vehicle in transport and two others running off the road
resulting in hitting a light pole and the other a hydrant. One criteria for all-way stops include 5 or
more reported crashes within a 12 month period that are susceptible to correction by a multi-
way stop. This intersection has zero, therefore this criteria is not met.
Minimum vehicle volumes where than reviewed. Approach volumes were utilized from the video
recording equipment for a 12 hour period starting at 6:30 am until 6:30 pm. Eight peak hour
intervals were than identified and then they were averaged over those 8 hours. On the major
approach, the average was 269 vehicles and the minor approach averaged 117 cars. The
minimum numbers required for this criteria is 300 vehicles per hour for the major street (both
approaches) and 200 units for the combined vehicle, pedestrian and bicycle volumes (both
approaches). Neither one of these criteria's were met.
Additional data was collected on Front Street to determine speed and volume. Front Street is
within the city limits in a urban district classification therefore by State Statues it is determined to
be a 30 mph speed limit. The 85th percentile speed is the speed at which 85 vehicles out of
100 are traveling at that speed or less. It was found that Front Street vehicles are traveling less

page.text: Agenda Item: Temporary Traffic Calming Measures
On October 7th, 2014 the site plan/traffic advisory committee noted a request from the
planning commission for a proposal on temporary measures for traffic calming. This
proposal would be for the installation such as traffic circles/roundabouts at select
locations for trial period of time. This will allow residents that are requesting traffic
calming to see if there are successful which then would eventually be programmed into
the Capital Improvements Plan for permanent installation. The City is in the process of
collecting pricing information for the various pieces of temporary traffic calming

page.text: Agenda Item: Long Range Transportation Plan (LRTP) Open House October 30
The MAPO’s LRTP open house meeting will be from 5 p.m. to 7 p.m.,
Thursday, October 30 at the Intergovernmental Center, 10 Civic Center Plaza. The
meeting will provide information about the planning process for the 2045 long-range
transportation plan including existing condition data, traffic analysis information and
future travel demand forecasts. Since citizen input is important and helpful, citizens are
invited to provide input about transportation issues, needs and opportunities.
Staff has followed the procedure outlined in the MAPO’s Public Participation Plan
regarding open houses. Specific actions taken by staff include:
• Meeting notice in Mankato Free Press
• Paid advertisement in Mankato Free Press (3 runs)
• Paid Advertisement in Minnesota State University Reporter (1 run)
• Direct mailing to properties owners along 3 key corridors.
• Meeting Information on MAPO web-site and facebook page
• Meeting flyer placed in transit facilities and in Intergovernmental Center
• Press release send out from the City of Mankato
• Email sent to individuals on MAPO’s interested parties list
• Direct interview /news story with Mankato Free Press
• Booth display at Envision 2020 event hosted by Greater Mankato Growth
